Caleb Jantsch¶

A1: Research Question¶

 Can an ARIMA model be used to produce a forecast of revenue for the next month?

A2: Goal of Analysis¶

 The goal of this analysis is to create a time series model that is able to create a reasonably accurate forecast of future revenue for the organization. Being able to anticipate future revenues is important for any organization in order to appropriately allocate company resources. For this analysis, we will look to see if a model can be created to forecast the revenue for the next month.

B: Assumptions of Time Series Analysis¶

Stationarity:¶

 In order to perform a time series analysis using ARIMA, the data must be stationary. For data to be stationary, its statistical properties, such as the mean and standard deivation, must remain constant over time. If you were to look at a visual of stationary data, it would be flat with no upward or downward trend, the variance of the data would be constant, and there would be no repeating seasonal patterns in the data (National Institute of Standards and Technology, n.d.).

Autocorrelation¶

 Autocorrelation is a measure of the similarity between a point and a lagged version of itself. In order for a time series analysis to be done, the data can not be autocorrelated. Doing an analysis on data with autocorrelation can lead to erroneous results (Dotis-Georgiou, 2019).

C2: Time Step Formatting¶

 The time series shows the company's daily revenue over a two year period. Each observation represents the revenue for a that specific date. There are 731 observations in the data which indicates that one of the years was a leap year. The data trends upwards over time with two large spikes in revenue during the first year and a large drop in revenue during the second year followed by a large increase in revenue. There are no gaps in the data.

C3: Stationarity¶

 Based on a visual inspection of the time series shown in C1, it is highly likely that the data is not stationary. This can be seen in the upward trend of the data. Additionally, the rolling mean and standard deviation on the graph are not constant over time. To confirm this, we will use the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test. The test yields a p-value of 0.32 which means that we accept the null hypothesis and the data is not stationary.

In [50]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller #check stationarity of data
In [51]:
# test data for stationarity and print results
result = adfuller(time)
print('Test Statistic:', result[0])
print('p-value:', result[1])
print('Critical Values:', result[4])

Test Statistic: -1.9246121573101842
p-value: 0.3205728150793961
Critical Values: {'1%': -3.4393520240470554, '5%': -2.8655128165959236, '10%': -2.5688855736949163}

 Now that we know that our original data is not stationary, we will take the difference of the data and see if that makes it stationary. Performing the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test on the differenced data doesn't yield a readable p-value. However, when we compare the test statistic to the critical values, we see that the test statistic well below the 5% threshhold, which indicates that our p-value is far below the necessary value of 0.05. Additionally, if we plot the differenced data and visual inspect it, we can see that the data is flat with no upward or downward trend. The data also appears to vary consistantly around the mean. With this we can say that the data is stationary if it is differenced one time. We will use this to set a value of 1 for d when performing our analysis later.

from pmdarima import auto_arima #used to determine optimal values for model

 To find the optimal values for our ARIMA model, we will use auto_arima. Auto_arima will go through and test out various values for our model and compare them using the models AIC values. It returns the model with the lowest AIC score as the best model for the data. Here, it returns an ARIMA(1,1,0) model which is consistent with our previous observations about the stationarity of the data and the acf and pacf plots.

 To confirm that the output of auto_arima is in fact the model with the lowest AIC score, we will run two for loops to test different p and q values in an ARIMA model and print out the results of the models with AIC scores lower than the previous best iteration. In the end, we confirm our auto_arima results with the code outputting an ARIMA(1,1,0) model as our best model.

In [73]:
# compare results againts an ARIMA model in a for loop
best_aic = 5000

for p in range(6):
    for q in range(6):
        try:
            test_model = ARIMA(time, order=(p, 1, q))
            test_results = test_model.fit()
            if test_results.aic < best_aic:
                best_aic = test_results.aic
                print(p, q, best_aic)
        except:
            continue

E1: Results of Analysis¶

Model Selection¶

 The process for selecting a model is as follows. First, we test the data for stationarity and took the difference of the data to determine the value of d for our ARIMA model. Since we were able to make the data stationary by taking the difference one time, d was set to 1. Next, we put our full data set into auto_arima to determine the p and q values that produced the lowest AIC score. Auto_arima suggested an ARIMA(1,1,0) model and we confirmed that this did produce the lowest AIC scores by testing p and q values in an ARIMA model using two for loops.

Predictions and Forecast Length¶

 For this analysis a prediction period of one month and a forecast length of one month were chosen. The reason for choosing these intervals is due to the inherent challenge of predicting the future. The longer the period you try to predict the more errors in the model add up and reduce the usefulness of the model. This can be seen by the large 95% confidence intervals seen in the visualizations of the predictions and forecast. These intervals represent the area in which we are confident that the actual values will lie. Since attempting to forecast a period further out would likely yield inaccurate and unrealiable results, a shorter period of one month was chosen.

Model Evaluation¶

 When we look at the diagnostics from our model we can conclude that it is a statistically significant model. A visual inspection of the diagnostics plot in section D4 shows that the residuals of our model are normally distributed and that there is no autocorrelation in the residuals. The normal distribution of the residuals can be in the Q-Q plot on the bottom left of the diagnostics plot and the histogram on the top right. In the Q-Q plot, the residuals follow the red line which indicates that they are normally distributed. In the histogram, we see that the orange line is very similar to the green line which shows a normal distribution. The lack of autocorrelation can be seen in acf plot on the bottom right of the plot and the plot of the residuals on the top left. In the acf plot, we see that the autocorrelation values are all in the 95% confidence interval, meaning that they do not vary significantly from zero. In the plot of the residuals, we see that the residuals resemble white noise with no observable patterns. These conclusions are further supported by the p-values for the Ljung-Box and Jarque-Bera test seen in the results summary of the model. The Ljung-Box test has a p-value of 0.98 which means we can accept the null hypothesis that the residuals are not autocorrelated. The Jarque-Bera test has a p-value of 0.36 which means we can accept the null hypothesis that the residuals are normally distributed.

 However, while our diagnostics show that our model is statistically significant, a visual inspection of our forecast along with the root mean squared error and mean absolute error of our training model indicate that it may not be practically useful. Looking at the plots for the predictions of our training model and the forecast of our final model, we see that our prediction is just a horizontal line with large 95% confidence intervals. In the training predictions versus test data plot seen in section E2, we see that while the test data lies entirely within the 95% confidence interval, the predicted values do not follow the upward or downward movement of the actual data. This can be seen in the rather large values for the root mean squared error and the mean absolute error. The RMSE had a value of 1.61 and the MAE had a value of 1.42. This means that the actual values of the data will likely differ greatly from our predicted values. This lack of precision means that our model does not offer much value from a practical business standpoint.

E3: Recommendations¶

 In section E1, we concluded that our model was not practically useful for providing business insight. However, there is the possibility that additional variables could provide the additional information we need to create a useful model. In the plot of our time series, we observe three events in the data that could prove useful if we are able to find their underlying cause. These events are the large increases in revenue seen in March and September 2023 and the large drop followed by a large increase in revenue beginning in August 2024. If we are able to find some other variable that is able to explain these events, we may be able to produce a practically useful model for predicting future revenue. Therefore, it is our recommendation that we look into further understanding these large changes in revenue for potentially useful insights.
